Summarise leaf damage data

I want to create two columns to merge with the GCMS data. First, a mean percent damage for each plant, second, the percent damage from the leaf the twister was on.

damage_summary <- leaf_damage %>% 
  group_by(plant.num) %>% 
  summarise(damage_mean.percent = mean(damage.percent))
twisterleaf <- leaf_damage %>% 
  filter(leaf.num == "T") %>% 
  select(plant.num, "damage_T" = damage.percent)
damage <- full_join(damage_summary, twisterleaf)
Joining, by = "plant.num"

Tidy GC data

#find compounds only in 3 or fewer samples to remove
remove <-
  gc %>% 
  group_by(Compound) %>% 
  summarize(count = sum(RPA>0)) %>% 
  filter(count < 4) %>% 
  .$Compound
gc_tidy <-
  gc %>%
  filter(!Compound %in% remove) %>% 
  #make joining by plant number easier
  separate(sample, into = c("plant.num", "when"), remove = FALSE)

Join all data

leafhopper_tidy <-
  left_join(gc_tidy, damage) %>% 
  select(sample, density_start, density_end, damage_mean.percent, damage_T, Compound, RPA)
Joining, by = "plant.num"

Transform and spread

Log transformation

Why?

leafhopper_tidy %>%
  filter(RPA > 0) %>%
  summarize(min = min(RPA))

I’ll add an offset an order of magnitude smaller than the smallest non-zero value (1e-8) and log transform. I also tried a centered log transform, but the values are too small and it produces NaN’s

leafhopper_tidy <-
  leafhopper_tidy %>% 
  mutate(offsetRPA = (RPA + 1e-8)*1000,
         logRPA = log(offsetRPA))

Spread these

leafhopper_logRPA <-
  leafhopper_tidy %>% 
  select(-RPA, -offsetRPA) %>% 
  spread(key = Compound, value = logRPA)
leafhopper_RPA <-
  leafhopper_tidy %>% 
  select(-logRPA, -offsetRPA) %>% 
  spread(key = Compound, value = RPA)

Centered log ratio transformation

This is for compositional data only, where only the relative amounts of metabolites matter, not differences in sums between samples (e.g. more leafhoppers = more volatiles). I should probably not use this. If I do end up treating this as compositional data, I should use a newer Isometric Log Ratio transformation that is better for interpretation.

library(Hotelling)
Loading required package: corpcor
leafhopper_CLR <-   
  leafhopper_tidy %>% 
  mutate(bigRPA = offsetRPA * 1000) %>% 
  select(-logRPA, -offsetRPA, -RPA) %>% 
  spread(key = Compound, value = bigRPA) %>% 
  select(-meta) %>%
  # do the CLR
  clr() %>% 
  # re-add metadata
  bind_cols(leafhopper_RPA %>% select(meta), .)

PCA
18 samples x 108 variables
standard scaling of predictors
plot(pca_clr, parAsColFcVn = leafhopper_CLR$density_end, parLabVc = leafhopper_CLR$sample)

I’m not really sure that one is better than the other. The loadings certainly change a lot—log transformation fucks with variance, so that’s not surprising. CLR seems to help things look more normal, but I think that will cause problems with interpretability. It’s probably best to use untransformed data, but it could be useful to show results of both untransformed and isometric log ratio transformed data.

Compare to PCA

No real pattern found in PCA on raw RPAs (in contrast to CLR transformed data, shown below)

Compositional PLSR

This uses CLR transformed data, which is appropriate for compositional data. That is, the relative amounts of metabolites are important and the differences in sums of RPAs between samples are not. I’m not sure that’s totally appropriate since I expect changes in composition and ammount. Might be worthwile to explore.
